The '''Brunei LNG''' (BLNG) is the [[Liquefied natural gas|LNG]] plant in [[Lumut, Brunei]]. Established in 1969 and was opened in 1973, it was the first LNG plant in the Western Pacific. The operating company—Brunei LNG Sdn Bhd—is owned by the Government of Brunei (50%), [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell Overseas Trading Limited]] and [[Mitsubishi Corporation]] (both 25%). Brunei LNG operates five [[LNG train]]s and produces 6.71&nbsp;million tonnes every year of liquified natural gas. It has approximately 500 personnel.<ref name="test">[http://www.blng.com.bn/about_history.html]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Facts and Figures.</ref>

The facility uses [[Air Products & Chemicals|Air Products]]' AP-C3MR process and has three LNG storage tanks capable of holding {{convert|195000|m3}}.{{cn|date=March 2016}}

Brunei LNG operates seven [[LNG carrier]]s through the joint venture company, Brunei Shell Tankers. The first four carriers were delivered between October 1972 and October 1975, with a maximum storage capacity of {{convert|77731|m3}}. These older ships were built in France. The three newer vessels were built in Korea (Amali/Arkat) and Japan (Abadi) by [[Daewoo Shipbuilding & Marine Engineering|Daewoo]] and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries|Mitsubishi Nagasaki respectively. The first of these three ships was delivered in June 2002, with the most recent ship, Amadi, being delivered in July 2011. These ships hold between {{convert|135000|and|148000|m3}} of LNG collectively. <ref>http://www.aukevisser.nl/supertankers/gas-SP/id703.htm</ref>

