'''Engkanto''' are mythical environmental [[spirit]]s that are said to have the ability to appear in human form.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Silliman University, James W. Chapman Research Foundation|year=1977|title=Silliman Journal|journal=Silliman Journal|publisher=Silliman University|pages=354|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=60gZAAAAIAAJ&q=Engkanto&dq=Engkanto|accessdate=2008-06-21}}</ref>  They are often associated with the spirits of ancestors in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=Aguilar>{{cite book|title=Clash of Spirits|first=Filomeno V. |last=Aguilar|year=1998|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=0-8248-2082-7}}</ref><ref name=VanRheenan>{{cite book|title=Contextualization And Syncretism: Navigating Cultural Currents|author=Gailyn Van Rheenen, Gailyn Van Rheenan|year= 2006|publisher=William Carey Library|isbn=0-87808-387-1| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E84GB2f2a9QC&pg=PA211&dq=Engkanto|accessdate=2008-06-21}}</ref><ref name=Demetrio>*{{cite journal  | last = Demetrio | first = Francisco   | year = 1969 | title = The Engkanto Belief: An Essay in Interpretation | journal = Asian Folklore Studies | volume = 28 | issue = 1| pages = 77–90  | jstor = 1177781| doi = 10.2307/1177781 }}</ref> They are also characterized as spirit sorts like sirens, dark beings, elves, and more.<ref name="ramos"/> Belief in their existence has likely existed for centuries,<ref name=Demetrio /> and continues to this day.<ref>*{{cite journal | year = 2003 | last = Borchgrevink | first = Axel | title = Ideas of Power in the Philippines | journal = Cultural Dynamics | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 41–69 | url = http://cdy.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/15/1/41 | accessdate = 2008-06-19 | doi = 10.1177/0921374003015001108}}</ref>

==Appearance==
Engkanto have many similarities to humans in that they age, appear to have male and female sexes, can suffer from illness and indeed even die. They are an object of mythology for many Filipinos. Often told by adults as stories and shown on media. They have different appearances. Some appear to be beautiful having blue eyes, fair complexion and golden hair.<ref name=Demetrio />  They may however have unusual features such as high-bridged noses, fair skin, blond hair and lack of [[philtrum]]. They have a wide range of appearances but one common fact of a different feeling or vibe than humans.<ref name="ramos">{{cite book |last=Ramos |first=Maximo D. |authorlink= |coauthors= |pages=55–56 |title=Creatures of Philippine Lower Mythology |year=1971 |publisher=University of the Philippines Press |location=Philippines |oclc=804797}} {{ISBN|971-06-0691-3}} (Quezon City Press, 1990)</ref> Other variants exhibit [[sexual dimorphism]] such as [[Bagobo]] spirits which are separated into the female ''tahamaling'' and the male ''mahomanay''. The female spirit is alleged to have red complexion while the male have a fair complexion.<ref name="ramos" /> Their dwellings will normally appear as natural features, for example large rocks or trees, or shadows in human form; although to humans they have befriended they can appear as magnificent palaces.<ref name=Demetrio /> These creatures prefer large trees and nature such as the ''[[Banyan|balete]]'' in which they also place their belongings.<ref name="ramos"/> An engkanto may choose to stay by a human's side as told by stories where characters are usually in either a sense of trance or a deep loss of energy. Engkanto may be good or bad.

==Capabilities==

Engkanto are most commonly known for either extreme malignant effects, or an overwhelming influence of luck. Those the Engkanto do not favor had become depressed, suffered from madness, or even disappeared for days or months, possibly as a result of the human possession.<ref name=Demetrio /><ref>{{cite journal |last=Tremlett |first=Paul-François |title=The Ethics of Suspicion in the Study of Religions |year=2007 |journal=DISKUS |volume=8 |url=http://www.basr.ac.uk/diskus/diskus8/Tremlett.htm |accessdate=2008-06-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416193040/http://www.basr.ac.uk/diskus/diskus8/Tremlett.htm |archivedate=2009-04-16 |df= }}</ref>  They are also said to be capable of causing [[fever]]s and skin diseases such as [[boil]]s. These spirits also sometimes lead travelers astray in the forest, even kidnap them. This, however, is said to be avoidable by bringing an "''[[Anting-anting]]''" or "''[[Agimat]]''" a piece of magical [[Amulet|charm]] or [[amulet]] that wards away evil spirits and prevents them from harming the wielder.<ref name=VanRheenan /> However, if they do favor someone they are generous and capable of bringing power and riches to that person.  [[Shamanism|Shaman]] often try to commune with Engkanto on holy days to obtain better healing powers from them, as well as learning how to better deal with evil spirits.<ref name=Demetrio />

==Study==
Francisco Demetrio made a study of 87 folk stories from [[Visayas]] and [[Mindanao]] relating to Engkanto. He contended the Engkanto were based on early European [[friars]].<ref name=Aguilar/><ref name=Demetrio/>

