'''Photobiology''' is the scientific study of the interactions of [[light]] (technically, [[non-ionizing radiation]]) and living [[organism]]s.<ref>{{cite web |author=Smith, Kendrick C. |year=2014 |url=http://www.photobiology.info/introduction.html |title=What Is Photobiology? |accessdate=2018-08-02 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The field includes the study of photophysics, photochemistry, [[photosynthesis]], [[photomorphogenesis]], [[visual system|visual processing]], [[circadian rhythm]]s, photomovement, [[bioluminescence]], and [[ultraviolet]] radiation effects.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=EGfSBwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA2&dq=photobiology&ots=C7lsO_Uo2j&sig=CLH0SGtEiM2d2nliXecEJ_wossM#v=onepage&q=photobiology&f=false|title=The Science of Photobiology|last=Smith|first=Kendric|date=2013-03-08|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781461580614|language=en}}</ref>
The division between [[ionizing radiation]] and non-ionizing radiation is typically considered to be a photon energy greater than 10 eV,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transition.fcc.gov/Bureaus/Engineering_Technology/Documents/bulletins/oet56/oet56e4.pdf |accessdate=2018-08-02 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020131849/http://transition.fcc.gov/Bureaus/Engineering_Technology/Documents/bulletins/oet56/oet56e4.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-20 |author1=Robert F. Cleveland, Jr. |author2=Jerry L. Ulcek |title=Questions and Answers about Biological Effects and Potential Hazards of Radiofrequency Electromagnetic Fields |publisher=OET (Office of Engineering and Technology) Federal Communications Commission |location=Washington, D.C. |edition=4th |date=August 1999}}</ref> which approximately corresponds to both the first ionization energy of oxygen, and the ionization energy of hydrogen at about 14 eV.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jim Clark |year=2000 |url=http://www.chemguide.co.uk/atoms/properties/ies.html |title=Ionisation Energy |accessdate=2018-08-02 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126131813/http://www.chemguide.co.uk/atoms/properties/ies.html |archivedate=2011-11-26}}</ref>
