{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}

In early [[military engineer]]ing, a '''saucisson''' ([[French language|French]] for a large, dry-filled [[sausage]]) was a primitive type of [[fuse (explosives)|fuse]], consisting of a long tube or hose of cloth or leather, typically about an inch and half in diameter (37&nbsp;mm), damp-proofed with [[pitch (resin)|pitch]] and filled with [[black powder]]. It was normally laid in a protective wooden trough, and ignited by use of a [[torch]] or [[slow match]]. Saucissons were used to fire [[fougasse (weapon)|fougasse]]s, [[petard]]s, [[Mining (military)|mines]] and [[camouflet]]s.

Very long [[fascine]]s were also called '''saucissons'''.

Later, in early 20th century [[mining]] [[jargon]], a '''saucisson''' referred to the flexible casings used for [[explosive]]s in mine operations.

